JAVA SPRING BOOT + SPRING + HIBERNATE + SERVLET ANNOTATIONS (FULL MASTER NOTES)

1. STEREOTYPE ANNOTATIONS (SPRING CORE)

1. @Component
Purpose: Generic annotation for any Spring-managed class
Used at: Class level
Why used: To tell Spring to create object automatically (Bean)

Example:
@Component
class DemoService {}

Use case:
Base annotation for all Spring beans

---

2. @Service
Purpose: Used for Business Logic Layer
Used at: Class level
Why used: To separate service logic from controller and DAO

Example:
@Service
class UserService {}

Use case:
Calculations, processing logic, validations

---

3. @Repository
Purpose: Used for Data Access Layer (DAO)
Used at: Class level
Why used:
- Handles database operations
- Converts SQL exceptions into Spring exceptions

Example:
@Repository
class UserRepository {}

Use case:
Database queries, JPA operations

---

4. @Controller
Purpose: Used for MVC Controllers (Web layer)
Used at: Class level
Why used: To handle HTTP requests and return views (JSP/HTML)

Example:
@Controller
class HomeController {}

Use case:
Traditional Spring MVC applications

---

5. @RestController
Purpose: Used for REST APIs
Used at: Class level
Why used:
- Combination of @Controller + @ResponseBody
- Returns JSON/XML directly

Example:
@RestController
class UserController {}

Use case:
REST APIs (modern backend applications)

---

6. @SpringBootApplication
Purpose: Main entry point of Spring Boot application
Used at: Class level (main class only)

Combination of:
- @Configuration
- @EnableAutoConfiguration
- @ComponentScan

Example:
@SpringBootApplication
class Application {}

Use case:
Starts Spring Boot application

---

2. REQUEST MAPPING ANNOTATIONS (SPRING MVC / BOOT)

7. @RequestMapping
Purpose: Maps HTTP requests to methods/classes
Used at: Class level + Method level

Example:
@RequestMapping("/api")
class UserController {}

@RequestMapping("/users")
method

Use case:
Generic mapping for all HTTP methods

---

8. @GetMapping
Purpose: Handle GET requests
Used at: Method level

Example:
@GetMapping("/users")

Use case:
Fetch data

---

9. @PostMapping
Purpose: Handle POST requests
Used at: Method level

Example:
@PostMapping("/users")

Use case:
Create new data

---

10. @PutMapping
Purpose: Handle PUT requests
Used at: Method level

Use case:
Update data

---

11. @DeleteMapping
Purpose: Handle DELETE requests
Used at: Method level

Use case:
Delete data

---

3. PARAMETER ANNOTATIONS (VERY IMPORTANT)

12. @PathVariable
Purpose: Extract value from URL path
Used at: Method parameter level

Example:
@GetMapping("/users/{id}")
public User getUser(@PathVariable int id)

URL:
/users/101

Output:
101 is extracted

Use case:
REST URLs with dynamic values

---

13. @RequestParam
Purpose: Get query parameters from URL
Used at: Method parameter level

Example:
@GetMapping("/users")
public User getUser(@RequestParam String name)

URL:
/users?name=sahil

Use case:
Filtering, searching data

---

14. @RequestBody
Purpose: Convert JSON request body into Java object
Used at: Method parameter level

Example:
@PostMapping("/users")
public void addUser(@RequestBody User user)

Use case:
POST/PUT requests with JSON data

---

4. SPRING MVC + BOOT SUPPORT ANNOTATIONS

15. @ResponseBody
Purpose: Converts Java object to JSON response
Used at: Method level

Example:
@ResponseBody
public User getUser()

Use case:
Return JSON without view page

Note:
Already included in @RestController

---

16. @ModelAttribute
Purpose: Bind form data to object
Used at: Method/Parameter level

Use case:
Spring MVC form handling

---

17. @ExceptionHandler
Purpose: Handle exceptions in controller
Used at: Method level

Example:
@ExceptionHandler(Exception.class)

Use case:
Custom error handling

---

5. HIBERNATE / JPA ANNOTATIONS

18. @Entity
Purpose: Marks class as database table
Used at: Class level

Use case:
ORM mapping

---

19. @Id
Purpose: Primary key
Used at: Field level

---

20. @GeneratedValue
Purpose: Auto increment primary key

---

21. @Table
Purpose: Custom table name

---

22. @Column
Purpose: Custom column name

---

23. @OneToOne
Purpose: One-to-One relationship

---

24. @OneToMany
Purpose: One-to-Many relationship

---

25. @ManyToOne
Purpose: Many-to-One relationship

---

26. @ManyToMany
Purpose: Many-to-Many relationship

---

6. SPRING BOOT ADVANCED ANNOTATIONS

27. @Configuration
Purpose: Define configuration class

---

28. @Bean
Purpose: Create custom Spring bean

---

29. @ComponentScan
Purpose: Scan packages for components

---

30. @EnableAutoConfiguration
Purpose: Auto configuration of Spring Boot

---

7. TRANSACTION + SERVICE LAYER

31. @Transactional
Purpose: Manage database transactions automatically
Used at: Class/Method level

Use case:
Commit / rollback handling

---

FINAL SUMMARY

Spring annotations are divided into:

1. Stereotype annotations (Component, Service, Repository)
2. Web annotations (Controller, RestController)
3. Request mapping annotations
4. Parameter annotations (PathVariable, RequestParam, RequestBody)
5. Hibernate/JPA annotations
6. Spring Boot annotations
7. Transaction annotations

---

INTERVIEW READY ANSWERS

Q1. What is @RestController?
It is used to create REST APIs and returns JSON response directly.

Q2. Difference between @Controller and @RestController?
@Controller returns view pages, @RestController returns JSON.

Q3. What is @PathVariable?
It is used to extract values from URL path.

Q4. What is @RequestBody?
It converts JSON request into Java object.

Q5. What is @Service?
It is used for business logic layer.

Q6. What is @Repository?
It is used for database layer and exception handling.

Q7. What is @SpringBootApplication?
It is combination of configuration, scanning, and auto configuration.
